# Why: Documenso ships with no Docker HEALTHCHECK directive. Coolify's
#      auto-restart logic only fires on container exit (process crash);
#      it can't detect a hung process where Node is alive but the app
#      stopped serving requests (DB connection lost, event loop blocked,
#      etc.). Without a healthcheck, a soft-failed container stays
#      "running" indefinitely with no traffic served.
#
#      The app already exposes `/api/health` at apps/remix/app/routes/
#      api+/health.ts which:
#        - issues `SELECT 1` against the configured DB
#        - calls `getCertificateStatus()` (warning if cert missing,
#          which is fine — we want startup to succeed when the operator
#          hasn't uploaded a cert yet)
#        - returns 500 only if DB is unreachable OR cert check throws
#        - returns 200 on ok / warning
#
#      That semantic is exactly right for a HEALTHCHECK: 500 → mark
#      unhealthy → Coolify restarts the container.
#
#      Timing rationale:
#        --start-period=60s : the app needs 10-30s after the container
#          starts to: run prisma migrate deploy, boot the Remix server,
#          warm the connection pool. 60s gives a 2x safety margin on
#          worst-case migration runs (we have 160 migrations as of
#          2026-05-04). During the start period, healthcheck failures
#          are NOT counted against retries — Coolify won't bounce
#          a still-booting container.
#        --interval=30s : every 30s after start period elapses. Each
#          check costs one `SELECT 1` and one stat() call, ~ms-level.
#          30s is the Docker default; smaller values would burn DB
#          round-trips with no real signal benefit.
#        --timeout=10s : if a check takes >10s, mark this attempt
#          failed. The local DB check should complete in <100ms; 10s
#          is generous enough to absorb Coolify-host disk pressure
#          during backup windows without false positives.
#        --retries=3 : need 3 consecutive failures (~90s) before
#          marking unhealthy. Tolerates transient network blips.
#
#      Implementation note: targets `127.0.0.1:3000` explicitly (NOT
#      `localhost`). Alpine's busybox wget resolves `localhost` via
#      `getaddrinfo`, which on dual-stack containers can prefer IPv6;
#      our Node server is bound to `HOSTNAME=0.0.0.0` (IPv4 only —
#      see docker/start.sh:31). Hard-coding the IPv4 loopback
#      sidesteps a previously-seen "Connection refused" failure mode.
#
#      Fragility: LOW. Only modifies the runner stage; doesn't touch
#      builder/installer. Upstream rarely changes the runner stage
#      below the CMD line, so worst-case at sync time is a 1-2 line
#      conflict. The HEALTHCHECK directive is independent of every
#      other line in the file.
#
#      Long-term: file an upstream PR adding HEALTHCHECK. Documenso's
#      docker/start.sh already prints `🏥 Health check: http://localhost:3000/api/health`
#      to operators, so the endpoint is clearly intended as the
#      canonical health surface.
#
diff --git a/docker/Dockerfile b/docker/Dockerfile
--- a/docker/Dockerfile
+++ b/docker/Dockerfile
@@ -148,4 +148,18 @@ COPY --chown=nodejs:nodejs ./docker/start.sh /app/apps/remix/start.sh

 WORKDIR /app/apps/remix

+# MODIFIED for BizRethink overlay 031: container-level health check.
+# Hits /api/health which probes DB connectivity + cert status. Returns
+# 500 if DB unreachable; 200 otherwise (cert missing is "warning",
+# acceptable on fresh installs). Targets 127.0.0.1 explicitly because
+# busybox wget on Alpine can prefer IPv6 from 'localhost' but the
+# Node server binds 0.0.0.0 (IPv4 only). 60s start period covers
+# prisma migrate deploy + Remix boot. See overlays/031 for details.
+HEALTHCHECK --start-period=60s --interval=30s --timeout=10s --retries=3 \
+  CMD wget --spider --quiet http://127.0.0.1:3000/api/health || exit 1
+
 CMD ["sh", "start.sh"]
